---
import ComponentLayout from '@/layouts/ComponentLayout.astro'
---

<ComponentLayout name='Flex'>
	<h2>Flex Layout System Documentation</h2>
	<p>
		This documentation outlines a collection of utility-first CSS classes designed to create
		flexible and responsive layouts using CSS Flexbox. These classes provide foundational
		building blocks for common layout patterns like stacking elements, creating rows, splitting
		content, and centering items.
	</p>

	<h3>Core Flex Classes</h3>
	<p>These classes leverage CSS Flexbox to control the arrangement and alignment of elements.</p>

	<h4>Stack</h4>
	<pre><code>.stack</code></pre>
	<p>
		Arranges items in a vertical column by default. This is useful for creating sections of
		content where elements should stack one after another.
	</p>
	<div class='stack'>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>1</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>2</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>3</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>4</div>
	</div>

	<h4>Cluster</h4>
	<pre><code>.cluster</code></pre>
	<p>
		Arranges items horizontally in a row. Items will wrap to the next line if there isn't enough
		space. This is ideal for lists of items or elements that should sit side-by-side.
	</p>
	<div class='cluster'>
		<div class='card center'>Item 1</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 2</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 3</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 4</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 5</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 6</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 7</div>
		<div class='card center'>Item 8</div>
	</div>

	<h4>Split</h4>
	<pre><code>.split</code></pre>
	<p>
		Arranges items horizontally, pushing the first item(s) to one end and the last item(s) to
		the other, with space distributed between them. This is commonly used for header-like
		elements where you might have a logo on the left and navigation on the right.
	</p>
	<div class='split'>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Left Item</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Right Item</div>
	</div>

	<h4>Center</h4>
	<pre><code>.center</code></pre>
	<p>
		Centers its child content both horizontally and vertically within the container. Useful for
		placing elements precisely in the middle of a given space.
	</p>
	<div
		class='center'
		style='height: 100px; border: var(--size-border-width) solid var(--c-gray-300);'
	>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Centered</div>
	</div>

	<h3>Spacing</h3>

	<pre><code>.gap-[size]</code></pre>
	<p>Applies consistent spacing (gap) between flex items.</p>

	<h3>Responsive Breakpoints</h3>

	<p>
		These utility classes offer responsive variations to change the flex direction at different
		screen sizes, following a mobile-first approach.
	</p>

	<h4>Tablet Breakpoint</h4>
	<p>Classes prefixed with `-tablet-` apply styles from tablet screens upwards.</p>

	<pre><code>.stack-tablet</code></pre>
	<p>
		Forces items into a column layout on tablet and larger screens, overriding a potential row
		layout from smaller screens.
	</p>

	<pre><code>.cluster-tablet</code></pre>
	<p>
		Forces items into a row layout on tablet and larger screens, overriding a potential column
		layout from smaller screens.
	</p>

	<h4>Desktop Breakpoint</h4>
	<p>Classes prefixed with `-desktop-` apply styles from desktop screens upwards.</p>

	<pre><code>.stack-desktop</code></pre>
	<p>Forces items into a column layout on desktop and larger screens.</p>

	<pre><code>.cluster-desktop</code></pre>
	<p>Forces items into a row layout on desktop and larger screens.</p>

	<h3>Example Usage</h3>

	<h4>Responsive Navigation Bar</h4>
	<p>A common pattern where navigation items stack on mobile and become a row on desktop.</p>
	<div class='stack cluster-desktop gap-xs'>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Nav Item 1</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Nav Item 2</div>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Nav Item 3</div>
	</div>

	<h4>Header with Logo and User Info</h4>
	<p>Using `split` to distribute elements within a header.</p>
	<div class='split'>
		<div class='card center padding-xs'>Logo</div>
		<div class='cluster gap-xs'>
			<div class='card center padding-xs'>User Avatar</div>
			<div class='card center padding-xs'>Settings</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</ComponentLayout>
